      This againBlah blah blah:Clover Health Inc., a health insurer backed =
by venture capitalist Chamath Palihapitiya, was swept up in meme-stock mani=
a on Tuesday, posting a second day of wild gains as retail investors banded=
 together to punish short-sellers betting against the company.Clover rallie=
d 86% to close at $22.15 in New York trading after briefly doubling intrada=
y. The gains erased five months of losses in the stock -- which formed part=
 of a broader selloff in Palihapitiya-backed companies -- in just two days.=
 Trading volume in Clover was more than 29 times the three-month daily aver=
age on Tuesday, with a record 718 million shares changing hands.The sudden =
flurry of demand comes after retail traders realized that short-sellers had=
 been swelling their bets against Clover, a move that left them vulnerable =
if the stock were to start rallying. The stock=E2=80=99s story -- like many=
 retail plays -- has left behind fundamentals with shares trading above $20=
, that=E2=80=99s more than twice the average analyst estimate.And:The firm =
came under pressure =E2=80=A6 after Hindenburg Research put out a report al=
leging that it misled investors, which Clover Health=E2=80=99s management d=
isputed. ...Some Reddit users are speculating that Clover Health could be t=
he next short squeeze, which is characterized by a high level of its shares=
 being sold short. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9CApes who missed on $GME! Listen =
up, $CLOV is ready to lift off!=E2=80=9D wrote one user who goes by u/pvr90=
 on Tuesday. Ape is a nickname for buyers of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc=
. shares, which have been among the most actively traded meme stocks in rec=
ent weeks.Here=E2=80=99s a rough outline of the meme-stock cycle:=09There i=
s a company.=09Bad things happen: It gets criticized for  misleading invest=
ors about federal investigations, it   operates movie theaters that are shu=
t in a pandemic, it   operates video-game stores in malls as games shift to=
 being sold online, it literally   files for bankruptcy.=09The stock goes d=
own, and valuation-focused investors sell it short, thinking it has further=
 to go.=09Retail investors on Reddit decide that (1) it is actually underva=
lued, (2) the short sellers are evil and immoral and must be punished, (3) =
punishing the short sellers will cause the stock to rocket to the moon and =
(4) this will all be pretty funny.=09Lots of Reddit investors buy the stock=
, short sellers capitulate, the stock goes up.=09The stock goes up to way, =
way higher than it was in=C2=A0Step 2, or at any point in the company=E2=80=
=99s history.=09A few people mildly and tentatively suggest=C2=A0that perha=
ps the stock=E2=80=99s current all-time-high stock price is not justified b=
y economic fundamentals.=09Reddit is not having it: Any time anyone says so=
mething even slightly critical about the fundamentals, Reddit traders rush =
to buy stock and call options, pushing the price up even more.The way to be=
come a meme stock is not just to be=C2=A0good; companies don=E2=80=99t beco=
me meme stocks because Redditors endorse a widespread consensus that they a=
re good operators in attractive markets. The way to become a meme stock is =
to be=C2=A0bad, then good; companies become meme stocks because Redditors g=
et mad at hedge funds for shorting them, so they buy them, so they go up, a=
nd it=E2=80=99s fun and more Redditors join in.[1]=C2=A0There is a lot to s=
ay about this cycle but here let=E2=80=99s talk about CEO incentives. There=
 is a usual set of stories=C2=A0that people tell about the incentives facin=
g public-company chief executive officers. If you are the CEO, it is good f=
or you if your company grows quickly and makes a lot of money. It is good f=
or you to prepare for the future, to anticipate trends, to move your compan=
y toward the next big thing. It is good for you to make money consistently,=
 to report steadily rising profits. These things are good primarily because=
 they make your company=E2=80=99s stock price go up, and since you are paid=
 largely in stock and own a lot of stock, you get richer as the stock price=
 goes up. They are good secondarily because, with a high stock price and a =
good reputation, you will have easy access to capital and you will be able =
to launch fun projects and make your company bigger and more important. And=
 they are good for softer, more social reasons. If you report consistent ri=
sing profits analysts will respect you and you will have nice interactions =
on earnings calls; you will be viewed as a good CEO and there will be flatt=
ering profiles of you in magazines. Your day-to-day life will be pleasant b=
ecause people will think=C2=A0you are doing a good job; also the money is g=
ood.Other things would be=C2=A0bad. If you have an accounting or regulatory=
 scandal, that=E2=80=99s bad. If you operate a tired brand in a declining i=
ndustry, that=E2=80=99s bad.=C2=A0Bankruptcy is obviously bad. If your comp=
any performs poorly, it will attract short sellers. The short sellers will =
push down the price of the stock, which is bad for your wallet (since you o=
wn a lot of stock). They will say mean things about you, which you will fin=
d embarrassing. Earnings calls will be awkward and unpleasant. As the stock=
 declines due to your company=E2=80=99s poor performance, people will blame=
 you for that performance, since after all you are the CEO. Activist invest=
ors will buy stock and try to fire you to improve performance. They might s=
ucceed. You=E2=80=99ll be out of a job, humiliated, with worthless stock.Su=
rely the public-company CEO having the most fun right now[2] is Adam Aron, =
the CEO of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc., who has embraced his meme-stock=
 status. (It has been widely reported=C2=A0that he wore no pants on a recen=
t=C2=A0interview with a YouTube trading influencer;=C2=A0Ranjan Roy argues =
that, if true, this was a good meme-stock investor-relations move, which is=
 plainly correct.) One reason that he is having a lot of fun is that he own=
s a lot of AMC stock and AMC stock is up 2,500% this year. Another reason t=
hat he is having a lot of fun is that he has=C2=A0issued=C2=A0hundreds of m=
illions=C2=A0of dollars of stock this year so that he can acquire theaters,=
 =E2=80=9Cgo on the offense,=E2=80=9D and make AMC a bigger and more import=
ant company. A third reason that he is having a lot of fun is that he is a =
hero to an army of online investors, who call him the =E2=80=9CSilverback=
=E2=80=9D; there=C2=A0is a lot to be said for being a beloved celebrity.The=
 way that Aron got here =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way he got rich, the way he was =
able to raise a war chest to go after acquisitions, the way he became an in=
ternet celebrity =E2=80=94=C2=A0was by running a company that was heavily s=
horted. That's not the only thing that had to go his way, but it=E2=80=99s =
a big one. If analysts and institutional investors had been=C2=A0thrilled=
=C2=A0by Aron=E2=80=99s response to the pandemic, if everything had gone ri=
ght in AMC=E2=80=99s business, then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, AMC traded as hi=
gh as=C2=A0$16.59 in April 2019, roughly a year before the pandemic; it tra=
ded as high as $7.76 in February 2020, just before the pandemic hit it.=C2=
=A0Let=E2=80=99s say that, instead of plummeting in March 2020, AMC had res=
ponded so well that it got back to its 2019 highs, and then=C2=A0doubled=C2=
=A0from there. That would get it to $33.18. It closed at $55.05 yesterday. =
