border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-=
bottom: 0;">Skew</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually, if a stock trade=
s at $50, it is more expensive to buy a put option allowing you to sell the=
 stock at $40 than it is to buy a call option allowing you to buy the stock=
 at $60. I mean that it is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmore expensive=E2=80=9D in the opt=
ions-pricing sense: The put option will have a higher implied volatility; w=
hen you plug inputs into the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/24099315.258690/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQmxhY2sl=
RTIlODAlOTNTY2hvbGVzX21vZGVsI0JsYWNrJUUyJTgwJTkzU2Nob2xlc19mb3JtdWxh/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBe37903df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">Black-Scholes formula</a> to get the price of the option=
, you=E2=80=99ll use a higher volatility input for the $40 put than you wil=
l for the $60 call. Using a higher volatility will make the price of the op=
tion higher than a lower volatility would. You=E2=80=99d use an even higher=
 volatility for a $30 put than for the $40 put, and an even lower one for a=
 $70 call than for the $60 call. (The $30 put will cost <em>fewer dollars=
=C2=A0</em>than the $40 put, because it is more out-of-the-money, but it wi=
ll be =E2=80=9Cmore expensive=E2=80=9D in the sense of implied volatility.)=
 The implied volatility of a stock option generally goes up as the strike p=
rice goes down. This is called =E2=80=9Cskew.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">There are two intuitive ways to think about=C2=A0skew. One is a=
 sort of conditional-realized-volatility explanation: Usually volatility go=
es up when stock prices go down, and goes down when prices go up.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9CStocks take the stairs up and the elevator down,=E2=80=9D they say: P=
rices move down faster than they move up; panic acts faster than greed. So =
a falling stock is more volatile than a rising one.=C2=A0Also small compani=
es are volatile; when they become big companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0when their s=
hares become more valuable =E2=80=94 they become less volatile. So if a sto=
ck is trading at $50 now, and you buy a call option struck at $80 because y=
ou think it will go to $80, you also probably think that=C2=A0<em>it will b=
e less volatile</em>=C2=A0when it gets to $80. If you buy a put option stru=
ck at $20 because you think it will go to $20, you also probably think that=
=C2=A0<em>it will be more volatile</em>=C2=A0when it gets to $20. So the im=
plied volatility of a $20-strike put should be higher than the implied vola=
tility of an $80-strike call, because the stock will be more volatile at $2=
0 than at $80.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other explanation is abo=
ut=C2=A0supply and demand for options: People mostly want to=C2=A0<em>buy=
=C2=A0</em>options to protect themselves against a market decline, so they =
buy lots of $20 put options. People mostly want to=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>=
options to get some extra yield out of their current positions with buy-wri=
te programs, so they sell lots of $80 call options. So the price of low-str=
ike put options gets pushed up and the price of high-strike call options ge=
ts pushed down, so implied volatility decreases as the strike price increas=
es.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This relationship has <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24099315.258690/aHR0cHM6Ly90d=
2l0dGVyLmNvbS9UaGVTdGFsd2FydC9zdGF0dXMvMTM1NDQ2NzUwNjE0OTMzMDk0Nw/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBd00f6834" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">existed since 1987</a>.[5] But now it is breaking down. Her=
e is a Wall Street Journal article about how <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/24099315.258690/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRp=
Y2xlcy9hbWMtb3RoZXItbWVtZS1zdG9ja3MtdHVybi1vcHRpb25zLW1hcmtldC11cHNpZGUtZG9=
3bi0xMTYyMzE0NDYwMj9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB52=
3a5bb2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sk=
ew is inverting in meme stocks</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Implied volatility, a measure of how turbulent traders expect stocks t=
o be over a given time frame, typically drops as stocks go up,and climbs wh=
en they fall.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the meme stocks have =
defied those expectations. As AMC share prices hit a record last week, impl=
ied volatility for the stock jumped to the highest level in around four mon=
ths, according to Susquehanna Financial Group. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">And typically, investors pay more to protect themselves from =
stock declines than they do for bullish wagers. That hasn=E2=80=99t been th=
e case at times in meme stocks and a handful of other bets over the past ye=
ar, like some special-purpose acquisition companies, analysts said.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThese traditional relationships between v=
olatility and stocks have been turned on their heads in meme stocks,=E2=80=
=9D said Chris Murphy, co-head of derivatives strategy at Susquehanna.</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With meme stocks neither of the tr=
aditional explanations quite works. Meme stocks become more volatile as the=
y go up: A small stock might be fairly volatile, but a small stock that is =
rocketing to the moon is much more volatile. AMC=E2=80=99s <em>realized=C2=
=A0</em>volatility over the last 12 months =E2=80=94=C2=A0the actual amount=
 it has bounced around on a daily basis =E2=80=94=C2=A0is 233%; a year ago =
that number was 106%.[6] AMC closed yesterday at $55.05; it closed a year a=
go at $5.99. The stock is up almost tenfold and volatility has doubled. Not=
 how it=E2=80=99s supposed to work!=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
lso meme-stock investors love buying far-out-of-the-money call options, bot=
h as a way to make big levered bets and as a way to=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24099315.258690/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3R=
vcHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC0be74622" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">manipulate the price of the underlying stock<=
/a>. On the other hand they are not looking to get=C2=A0<em>insurance=C2=A0=
</em>by buying puts. (Though some number of meme-stock skeptics will bet=C2=
=A0<em>against=C2=A0</em>them by buying puts.)=C2=A0So there is a ton of de=
mand for out-of-the-money calls and less demand for out-of-the-money puts, =
so the supply-and-demand explanation for skew is reversed.=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so for instance AMC=C2=A0$80 strike calls expirin=
g on July 16 are trading at an implied volatility of around 306%; July 16 $=
44 strike puts are trading at around 282%. GameStop July 16 $400 strike cal=
ls trade at around 200% implied volatility; $200 strike puts trade at aroun=
d 184%.[7] Normally=C2=A0it would be the opposite, and it still is in most =
stocks. Microsoft Corp. July 16 $300 calls trade at about 24%, $200 puts tr=
ade at about 39%.=C2=A0But meme stocks don=E2=80=99t work like most stocks.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24099315.258690/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudHJhZGVyc2l=
uc2lnaHQubmV3cy90cmFkZXJzLWluc2lnaHQvc2VjdXJpdGllcy9vcHRpb25zL3doby1pcy1idX=
lpbmctYW1jLTE0NS1jYWxscy1pdC1tYXktbm90LWJlLXdoby15b3UtdGhpbmsv/607f07ceef4b=
